03:14.629 --> 03:28.242
According to this familiar New Testament text that we find in John chapter 13, we encounter the tension that exists between the old and the new.

03:29.474 --> 03:38.445
According to this particular text, Jesus shares with his disciples a new commandment.

03:39.747 --> 03:49.398
According to our Savior and Lord, Jesus says, love one another the way I have loved you.

03:49.438 --> 03:58.930
The old command to love, we find in Leviticus 19, Deuteronomy 6,

03:59.426 --> 04:10.382
In Mark 12, the great commandment that says, love God with all your mind, heart, soul, and strength, and love your neighbor as you love yourself.

04:10.402 --> 04:21.778
But now here, as Jesus prepares for his crucifixion and resurrection, Jesus shares not the old command, but a new command.

04:22.900 --> 04:27.186
Jesus doesn't say love your neighbor as you love yourselves.

04:27.810 --> 04:30.553
But now Jesus raises the bar.

04:32.195 --> 04:42.067
Jesus says, I want you to love your neighbor, not as you love yourselves, but love your neighbor the way I have loved you.

04:42.107 --> 04:57.426
